  "2396": "طَرِيقَةٌ and related words stem from the root ط-ر-ق, with the root verb طَرَقَ meaning \"he trod\" or \"he beat a path.\" طَرِيقَةٌ means \"method,\" \"manner,\" or \"way.\" The term highlights the idea of an established course of action or a habitual manner of doing something, reflecting the root's emphasis on treading or forming a path. This connection highlights the notion of a customary approach or conduct, developed through repeated practice, and signifies a defined way or method in which actions are carried out.",
  "2397": "طَرِيٌّ and related words stem from the root ط-ر-و, with the root verb طَرَا meaning \"it was fresh\" or \"it became moist.\" طَرِيٌّ means \"fresh,\" \"tender,\" or \"soft.\" The connection lies in the state of being newly formed or moist, directly relating to the root's emphasis on freshness. This term describes objects or substances that are supple or not dried out, symbolizing vitality and newness. It highlights qualities of softness and freshness, often associated with food or natural materials, emphasizing purity and life.",
